<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-10T16:16:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-10T16:16:00-05:00" n="50" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d50">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 835.73/81</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Argentina</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Robbins</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Buenos Aires</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-10T17:00:00-04:16">
                                    <hi rend="italic">August 10, 1918, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Embassy’s April 24, 11 a.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d50fn1">Not
                                printed.</note> Doctor Martienzo, Attorney General of the Republic,
                            to whom the petition of the Central &amp; South American Telegraph Co.
                            to lay a cable from Buenos Aires to Montevideo was referred, has given
                            us his opinion that such petition should be granted and that the laying
                            of this cable will in no way contravene the concession previously
                            granted the Western Telegraph Co. Both national Attorneys General have
                            now rendered a favorable opinion and I understand that the presidential
                            decree formally granting the company’s petition will shortly be issued.
                            The Western Telegraph Co. has now no further recourse beyond that of
                            requesting a reconsideration of the Attorney Generals’ decision.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Robbins</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>